JOHANNESBURG - The rand extended its losses against hard currencies on Wednesday afternoon after the ANC national policy conference confirmed it wanted the Reserve Bank to be state owned.The ANC had resolved to nationalise the Bank though the party said it would guarantee continued independence.READ: Gigaba to take Public Protector s Absa, SARB report on reviewThe role of the Bank had already been in focus after Public Protector Busisiwe Mkhwebane recommended that the Constitution be amended to change the mandate in favour of what the party called socio-economic protection of South Africans.At 3.31pm the rand was at R13.4155 to the dollar from R13.1889 and at R15.1879 to the euro from R14.9653. It was at R17.3146 to the pound from R17.0409.The euro was at $1.132 from $1.1346The government gained nothing in terms of concrete ability to direct the Reserve Bank through simple ownership and the bigger issue remained that of the Bank s mandate said Nomura emerging market economist Peter Attard Montalto. But it was a clear and worrying statement of intent which had raised questions for markets and ratings agencies said Attard Montalto.The rand had been on a weaker footing on Wednesday morning. Global sentiment had turned negative after North Korea launched an intercontinental ballistic missile on Tuesday.Markets were also watching for the minutes of the US Federal Reserve s June meeting which were due to be released after the close of the JSE.The Fed minutes had added to risk-off sentiment said Rand Merchant Bank currency strategist John Cairns.iNet Bridge